          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829241?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年 5 月，土耳其支持的一名宪兵在叙利亚西北部据报道被阿布·侯赛因·古莱希 (Abu al-Husayn al-Qurayshi) 使用的房屋外站岗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Bakr Alkasem/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108092"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 2:57 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伊斯坦布尔——伊斯兰国周四证实，其鲜为人知的最高领导人已被杀，这是该极端组织的高级领导人在不到两年的时间里第三次遭遇这种命运。</p><p>该组织在其发言人的一份音频声明中表示，其前任领导人代号阿布·侯赛因·古莱希 (Abu al-Husayn al-Qurayshi) 在与控制叙利亚西北部部分地区的敌对武装组织沙姆解放组织 (Hayat Tahrir al-Sham) 的冲突中身亡。 。</p><p>几个月前，土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-leader-killed-in-intelligence-operation-turkeys-erdogan-says-93f844cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，伊斯兰国领导人在土耳其在叙利亚北部的一次情报行动中被打死</a>。</p><p>该组织任命了新领导人阿布·哈夫斯·哈希米·古莱希 (Abu Hafs al-Hashimi al-Qurayshi)。据极端主义专家称，该组织的最新任最高指挥官在负责该组织期间没有发表公开声明。</p><p> 2014年，“伊斯兰国”控制了伊拉克和叙利亚大片地区，对数百万人实施残酷的宗教统治，并在全球范围内发起针对平民的暴力袭击行动。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>经过伊拉克和叙利亚军队在美国空军支持下多年的压倒性军事行动后，该组织于 2019 年失去了对叙利亚最后一块领土的控制。</p><p>该组织一直是一个地下激进组织，仍然有能力实施致命暴力。 2022 年初，其武装分子在叙利亚东部越狱，导致与美国支持的叙利亚军队进行了数天的巷战。大约 500 人在暴力事件中死亡。</p><p>伊斯兰国已无法重拾昔日在叙利亚和伊拉克的势头，但也在阿富汗和非洲部分地区设有分支机构。</p><p>该组织仍然面临着美国领导的叙利亚和伊拉克联军的压力。 7月，美国军方表示，他们在叙利亚的一次空袭中打死了一名伊斯兰国领导人。</p><p>该组织的前任高级领导人于 2022 年在一次与美国无关的行动中被叙利亚武装分子杀害。另一名高级领导人于 2022 年初在美国突击队的一次突袭中被杀。</p><p>写信给 Jared Malsin： <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.malsin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 18:57:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3<author><![CDATA[Jared Malsin]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What Is Happening in Niger? What to Know About the Coup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国西非反恐盟友民选总统下台引发军事干预威胁<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829069/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。法新社/盖蒂图片社<span>法新社/盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 2:34（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>尼日尔精锐总统卫队官员上周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拘留了这个西非国家的民选总统</a>穆罕默德·巴祖姆，并宣布自己为该国新领导人。这次政变令美国和欧洲政府感到震惊，这些国家一直与巴祖姆和尼日尔军队密切合作，打击非洲萨赫勒地区的伊斯兰武装分子。</p><p>尼日尔的一些西非邻国（主要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国和欧洲结盟</a>）威胁要使用武力恢复巴祖姆的地位。其他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯结盟的</a>国家则表示，他们将捍卫尼日尔的新军政府。</p><h3>美国和欧洲政府为何担心尼日尔政变？</h3><p>尼日尔一直是美国和欧洲<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">打击基地组织和伊斯兰国武装分子</a>的中心，这些武装分子近年来在撒哈拉以南的半干旱地区萨赫勒地区杀害了数千人。在马里和布基纳法索军方领导的政府驱逐了一直在那里与伊斯兰叛乱分子作战的法国和其他西方军队后，尼日尔变得更加重要。美国已花费约 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，配备从帐篷、收音机到侦察机和装甲运兵车等各种装备。美国在尼日尔驻有约 1,100 名士兵，他们训练当地特种部队并为他们执行任务提供建议。法国在尼日尔驻有大约 1,500 名士兵。</p><p>欧盟还依赖世界上最贫穷国家之一的尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-considers-substantial-fund-for-africa-to-deal-with-migrants-1440871414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来阻止非洲移民</a>进入利比亚并从那里进入欧盟。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="819" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828956?width=1260&amp;height=819" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">政变支持者在尼亚美示威期间悬挂俄罗斯国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>什么是西共体？它能扭转政变吗？</h3><p>西非国家经济共同体是一个由 15 个西非国家组成的政治和经济组织，其中包括尼日利亚、加纳和塞内加尔等地区重量级国家。周日，西非经共体领导人在一次紧急峰会上给尼日尔新军政府规定了 7 天的期限，以释放巴祖姆并让他重新担任总统。此后，该组织领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁要对尼日尔发动军事干预</a>，以恢复巴祖姆的权力。他们还对尼日尔实施了一系列严厉的金融和贸易制裁，希望迫使军政府做出让步。这些制裁包括冻结尼日尔在地区中央银行的资产以及切断尼日利亚的电力供应。尼日尔约 70% 的电力从尼日利亚购买。</p><p>作为回应，马里和布基纳法索的政变也受到西非经共体的谴责，它们警告说，他们将把对尼日尔的武装干预视为宣战，并将保卫尼亚美军政府。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828965?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲和美国公民从尼日尔撤离后抵达罗马附近的机场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：雷莫·卡西利/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>美国如何回应？</h3><p>拜登总统和国务卿安东尼·布林肯呼吁释放巴祖姆并保护尼日尔的民主。然而，美国官员一直小心翼翼地避免将军方的行动称为政变，这一名称将引发美国法律<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对军事援助的限制</a>。国防部表示，没有计划将军事人员或装备撤出尼日尔，并支持通过外交途径解决局势。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=2AE037D3-6705-43B5-828C-C117387FADDD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔上周发生政变后，欧洲各国政府和美国下令从尼日尔撤离本国公民。军政府领导人表示，军方不会屈服于压力，要求让被罢黜的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆复职。照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>拜登政府尚未表示美国是否会为西非经共体可能对尼日尔进行的军事干预提供后勤或其他支持。 “我们支持西非经共体的努力，包括施加压力，”布林肯周四表示。美国国务院已下令<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">撤离美国驻尼亚美大使馆的所有非必要人员</a>以及美国大使馆工作人员的家属。</p><p>与法国不同的是，美国尚未从尼日尔全面撤离美国公民。法国本周向尼日尔派遣了多架撤侨航班，并表示已帮助约 40 名美国公民离开该国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828970?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆与美国和欧洲政府密切合作，打击伊斯兰激进分子。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路透社/媒体库</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>俄罗斯对尼日尔政变持何立场？</strong></h3><p>俄罗斯政府呼吁尼日尔恢复宪法秩序，并警告不要进行武装干预。叶夫根尼·普里戈任,</p>他的准军事瓦格纳集团已经在马里拥有战士，他赞扬了这次政变，并向尼亚美军政府提供了雇佣军服务。<p></p><p>法国外交部长本周将周末针对法国大使馆的支持政变抗议活动归咎于俄罗斯的虚假信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="390" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829050?width=700&amp;height=390" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">军政府首脑、尼日尔自称领导人奥马尔·查尼将军率领总统卫队发动了政变。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ORTN/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>奥马尔·奇亚尼将军是谁？</h3><p>奥马尔·齐亚尼将军，有时也被称为阿卜杜拉哈马内，是发动反对巴祖姆起义的总统卫队队长。他现在作为尼日尔自封的领导人领导军政府。据熟悉尼日尔局势的人士透露，巴祖姆一直在考虑是否解雇蒂亚尼，这是政变的触发因素之一。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——威廉·莫尔丁对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟 (Gabriele Steinhauser)，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 18:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc<author><![CDATA[Gabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>奥马尔·齐亚尼</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Rags-to-Riches Female Candidate Shakes Up Mexico Presidential Race]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>小时候卖玉米粉蒸肉的索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 与总统洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔 (López Obrador) 发生争执，并为沮丧的反对派提供鼓励<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828458/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="霍奇特尔·加尔维斯最近在蒂华纳竞选，在墨西哥反对派联盟总统提名的竞选中处于领先地位。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>霍奇特尔·加尔韦斯最近在蒂华纳竞选，在墨西哥反对派联盟总统提名的竞选中处于领先地位。桑迪·赫法克 (Sandy Huffaker) 供职于《华尔街日报》<span>桑迪·赫法克 (Sandy Huffaker) 供职于《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105162"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105162"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jose-decordoba" itemprop="url" rel="author">何塞·德·科尔多瓦</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-montes" itemprop="url" rel="author">胡安·蒙特斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>墨西哥库埃纳瓦卡——Xóchitl Gálvez 穿着长及脚踝的传统土著服饰，大步走进挤满人的礼堂，商界人士起立鼓掌，高呼“Xóchitl”！霍奇特尔！</p><p>自 6 月参加墨西哥总统竞选以来，60 岁的加尔韦斯似乎让沮丧的反对派兴奋不已，并使总统安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔感到不安，他的执政党莫雷纳党预计将在明年的总统选举中轻松获胜，凭借民众的支持领导的燕尾服。</p><p>几周之内，加尔韦斯就将自己定位为十几个赢得墨西哥反对派联盟提名的候选人中明显的领跑者。候选人将于 9 月 3 日初选后确定。</p><p>洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔不再参选是因为<strong>&nbsp;</strong>墨西哥不允许连任。他很可能会祝福墨西哥城前市长克劳迪娅·谢因鲍姆，后者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexican-presidential-hopefuls-kick-off-race-to-succeed-lopez-obrador-70b16467?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">有望赢得党内提名</a>。在民意调查中，她领先莫雷纳的另一位希望之星、前外交部长马塞洛·埃布拉德(Marcelo Ebrard)约10个百分点。</p><p>反对派选民<strong>&nbsp;</strong>在加尔韦斯介入之前，他已经接受了莫雷纳在 2024 年选举中取得压倒性胜利。</p><p>这位鲜为人知的参议员经常骑着电动自行车出行，她有一个引人入胜的个人故事，从年轻女孩的街头小贩成长为成功的女商人和当选官员。她的支持者说，她传达的妇女权利、支持墨西哥人民对美好生活的渴望以及民族团结的信息，给因洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的分裂政治而疲惫不堪的墨西哥人带来了希望。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="816" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828495?width=1260&amp;height=816" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Xóchitl Gálvez 骑着自行车游览墨西哥城。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿尔弗雷多·埃斯特雷拉/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828461?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 的平易近人的举止、朴实的语言和对戏剧手势的喜爱吸引了普通墨西哥人。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的桑迪·赫法克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>墨西哥政治分析人士表示，加尔韦斯最近在民调中的支持率上升很大程度上要归功于洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔本人，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/think-u-s-politics-is-exhausting-mexicos-president-has-a-news-conference-every-morning-11565626849?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">每天都在早间新闻发布会上猛烈抨击她</a>，嘲笑她自力更生的故事，并提高了她在全国的知名度。</p><p>民意调查专家尤利塞斯·贝尔特兰 (Ulises Beltrán) 表示：“她是一个引人注目的现象。”他指出，她以两位数的优势领先最接近的反对派竞争者。</p><p>洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的发言人否认总统在政治上提振了加尔维斯，并将她的崛起归因于媒体的有利报道。他拒绝对总统竞选发表评论。</p><p>正在寻求提名的执政党成员、前参议员里卡多·蒙雷亚尔表示，洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔发表有关加尔韦斯的言论是为了动员他的政治基础。</p><p> “他把差异说得一清二楚是正确的，”他说。</p><p>虽然加尔韦斯作为一名女商人的成功吸引了墨西哥的政治和经济机构，但她平易近人的举止、朴实的语言和对戏剧手势的喜爱却赢得了普通墨西哥人的青睐。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3e8d3948-b604-4789-979f-3b0c2356e368.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xbgzW1zoD8k" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">她戴着银色假发，头戴白色瓜亚贝拉，在 2018 年的一段视频中模仿了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔</a>，该视频在 YouTube 上获得了数万次观看。去年，她穿着绿色霸王龙服装冲进参议院，抗议洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔提议的选举改革，她说这将使墨西哥“回到侏罗纪时代”。</p><p>加尔韦斯（Gálvez）的名字 Xóchitl 发音为“SOH-cheel”，在纳瓦特尔语中意为“花”，他的父亲是土著奥托米人，母亲是混血儿妇女，出生在特帕佩克（Tepatepec）。特帕佩克是一个昏昏欲睡的小镇，约有 11,000 人，周围环绕着郁郁葱葱的玉米地，车程约两小时。 &#39; 从墨西哥城开车过来。</p><p>加尔维斯说，她酗酒的父亲（现已去世）经常殴打她的母亲，有一次威胁要用猎枪射击母亲后，半夜将妻子和女儿赶出了家门。</p><p>她的表弟拉蒙·加尔韦斯 (Ramón Gálvez) 说，小时候，她与父母和四个兄弟姐妹睡在距离镇主广场几个街区的一栋单层土坯房的同一个房间里。房子没有自来水，一家人不得不收集雨水。他们与住在另外两个房间的七名亲戚共用一个厕所。</p><p> “这是一种充满暴力和贫困的生活，”她说。加尔维斯说，为了维持生计，她帮助母亲在街上卖果冻和玉米粉蒸肉。她说，当她父亲反对她读六年级以上时，她反抗了他。</p><p> “如果有什么东西定义了她，那就是她渴望变得更好，”表弟马可·安东尼奥·鲁伊斯说。</p><p> 17 岁时，加尔韦斯离开特帕佩克，来到墨西哥城贫民区的一间金属板搭建的单间小屋。她在接受采访时说，她早上担任电话接线员，晚上在墨西哥国立自治大学学习工程学，并在那里获得了奖学金。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="814" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828562?width=1260&amp;height=814" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总统安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的政党有望赢得下次选举。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：isaac esquivel/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="805" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828463?width=1260&amp;height=805" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 的一位支持者在最近的一次竞选集会上举着一块牌子，上面写着“Xambeadora”，这是墨西哥“勤奋者”一词与她名字的组合。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的桑迪·赫法克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>由于对计算的着迷，她创立了一家为智能建筑提供设备的高科技公司。 1999年，她被列入世界经济论坛的100位未来全球领导人名单。第二年，猎头公司向总统文森特·福克斯推荐她领导一个土著事务研究所，她一直担任到 2006 年。</p><p> 2018 年，她成为保守派国家行动党 (PAN) 的参议员，尽管她不是党员。</p><p> “她的人生故事超越了墨西哥国家故事的任何戏剧性剧本，”参议员同事、国家行动党前主席古斯塔沃·马德罗说。</p><p>民意调查专家贝尔特兰表示，加尔韦斯作为候选人的优势在于，她颠覆了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔对反对派的讽刺，认为后者代表了富裕、腐败和保守的寡头政治。</p><p> “信息就是信使，”政治分析家、墨西哥前外交部长豪尔赫·卡斯塔涅达 (Jorge Castañeda) 说。 “她让洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的身份政治对他有利。”</p><p>民意调查专家亚历杭德罗·莫雷诺表示，加尔韦斯还吸引了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔政党的传统选民。 “她对女性、老年人和受教育程度较低的人很有吸引力，”他说。</p><p>尽管如此，在 El Financiero 报纸最近的一项民意调查中，加尔维斯仍落后 Sheinbaum 10 个百分点。</p><p>加尔维斯表示，她支持总统的社会计划，但认为这些计划应该更加有效。她认为自己的个人故事是对洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔对像她这样的墨西哥奋斗者的蔑视的谴责。</p><p>在总统透露了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔公司合同的财务数据后，加尔韦斯对洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔提起了两项刑事诉讼。她说这些数据包括机密的税务信息，她说这些信息是非法获得的。洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔没有透露它来自哪里。他的发言人表示，法官将确定洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔是否做了不当或非法的事情。</p><p>加尔维斯偶尔会用墨西哥俚语和咯咯的笑声来反驳洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的攻击。</p><p> “他是个大男子主义，我一生中和很多大男子主义打过交道，”她说。</p><p>六月，在他错误地表示她想拿走老人的养老金后，她要求他道歉。在他拒绝后，她向法院提起诉讼，并获得裁决，赋予她在同一论坛上作出答复的权利。</p><p> “我不会在战斗中退缩。当他向我提出质疑时，我就上了法庭，”她说。</p><p>拿着法院命令，加尔维斯骑着自行车前往总统府，洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔正在那里举行上午的新闻发布会。 She knocked on the heavy wooden doors to the palace, but the president refused to let her in. Gálvez finally left.</p><p> Her failed attempt generated a wave of support, leading her to think hard about running for president. Two weeks later, she announced her candidacy. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828487?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Xóchitl Gálvez&#39;s message of women&#39;s rights, support for struggling Mexicans&#39; aspirations for a better life and of national unity has resonated with some Mexicans.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carlos Moreno/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to José de Córdoba at <a href="mailto:jose.decordoba@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jose.decordoba@wsj.com</a> and Juan Montes at <a href="mailto:juan.montes@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">juan.montes@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86<author><![CDATA[José de CórdobaJuan Montes]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Domestic Violence</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Social Issues</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Xóchitl Gálvez</category><category> Andrés Manuel López Obrador</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>domestic violence</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>social issues</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[In Saudi Arabia’s Ukraine Peace Talks, How to Measure Success?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Questions around Jeddah talks include who will turn up, whether participants will agree on date for peace summit <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107221"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="564" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828857?width=860&amp;height=564" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Crown Prince Mohammad Bin Salman of Saudi Arabia, where talks about a future peace between Ukraine and Russia are due to take place this weekend.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107221"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Laurence Norman</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 9:58 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Senior officials from up to 30 countries will meet in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, this weekend to talk about <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-to-host-ukraine-peace-talks-as-part-of-western-effort-to-woo-global-south-244f03f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">peace in Ukraine</a> —but this won&#39;t be a typical peace conference.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-and-allies-plan-peace-summit-without-russia-72341551?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Russia won&#39;t be there</a> . The idea isn&#39;t to come up with prescriptive terms for what a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-ukraines-deadly-drones-putins-invasion-and-bidens-limits-5f2f2cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">future peace deal between Ukraine and Russia</a> should look like. And the Saudi hosts aren&#39;t expected to do much in the way of communicating outcomes. As of Thursday, they hadn&#39;t even publicly confirmed that the event is happening.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Nonetheless, the meeting is part of a potentially important process that Ukraine and its Western backers hope can lead to the crafting of a shared set of principles with important developing countries for framing future peace talks to Kyiv&#39;s advantage. Many of those developing countries, such as Brazil, India and South Africa, have been largely neutral on the war.</p><p> Ukraine and European officials hope the process will lead to a major peace summit where the participants can sign off a shared vision of how the war should end.</p><p> Russian officials sent mixed signals this week about how they see the process, which started with a late-June meeting in Denmark. The Kremlin said it would be watching closely while Russian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Maria Zakharova called the gathering a “hoax.”</p><p> Here are some of the issues on which Ukraine and its backers will judge whether the Jeddah meeting is a success:</p><h3> Who turns up?</h3><p> Ukraine and Saudi Arabia sent invitations last week to around 30 countries, double the number of capitals that participated in June&#39;s Copenhagen meeting. Some countries may dial in rather than turn up.</p><p> The US and several European countries—including Britain, France, Germany and Poland—are expected to be there. So are South Africa, Turkey, India and Brazil. But there are doubts about how many developing countries will come and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">big question surrounding China</a> . Beijing ignored the Copenhagen talks, but US and European officials said this week that China appeared likely to send a representative to Jeddah. As Russia&#39;s most important foreign ally, China is seen as crucial to build traction behind the talks.</p><h3> Path to peace summit?</h3><p> The meeting will be seen as a major success if it produces a declaration at the end with a specific set of shared principles for framing peace talks and sets a date for the peace summit that Ukraine hopes to host this year. People involved in the process had talked down the likelihood of either of those happening, but a senior European diplomat said on Thursday that these goals aren&#39;t impossible.</p><h3> The Zelensky peace formula?</h3><p> The extent to which the talks embrace parts of President Volodymyr Zelensky&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/ukraine-zelensky-biden-congress-washington-trip-russia/card/zelensky-says-biden-supports-his-peace-plan-niPc0HGjRkabUKS9mL5A?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">10-point peace plan</a> will be key. Diplomats said Ukraine pressed for broad backing for its plan at the Copenhagen meeting, and the key developing countries said that wasn&#39;t going to happen. A particular sticking point: Ukraine&#39;s call for all Russian troops to withdraw before peace talks can start is seen as an obstacle to peace by some countries.</p><p> European officials say they hope to use the Ukraine plan—which also deals with prisoners of war, nuclear safety and food and energy security—to frame the issues in Jeddah. They would be eager to see working groups of the participants discuss each of the points in more detail at some point. But they warn that whatever eventually emerges from the talks will likely be a list of key principles of international law that everyone can embrace: support for territorial sovereignty and integrity, the application of international law, and the need for conflict to be resolved through dialogue and not the use or threat of force.</p><h3> Russia home alone?</h3><p> From the start, Ukraine and its Western backers were <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/changing-places-europeans-grow-more-assertive-on-ukraine-as-washington-shows-caution-e4b83acf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">clear that Russia wouldn&#39;t be invited</a> . They wanted to build support among developing countries for a durable and fair peace, which they believe should favor Ukraine as a victim of the Russian invasion. However, Western diplomats acknowledge that, at some point, if the talks are to lead to something, there will need to be eventual negotiations between Ukraine and Russia.</p><p> According to people involved in the talks, several developing countries questioned the absence of Russia in Copenhagen. Mexican President</p> Andrés Manuel López Obrador said this week his country would only participate in Jeddah if Russia was there. The extent of pressure from developing countries to bring Russia on board soon will be important.<p></p><h3> Western unity?</h3><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-nato-summit-membership-fb0d863a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Last month&#39;s NATO summit</a> underscored that even when only Ukraine and its Western backers are in the room, sparks can fly, with Zelensky initially denouncing a NATO communiqué that offered no clear path for Ukraine to join the alliance.</p><p> Tensions between Ukraine and its Western backers over the talks will be a sign of trouble. European diplomats have been pressing Ukraine to keep their ambitions in check for the talks and pushed back against some of Kyiv&#39;s proposals, including its hope to win backing among developing countries for imposing sanctions on Russia. Several Western diplomats said after the Copenhagen talks that the degree of Ukraine&#39;s flexibility will be make or break for the talks.</p><p> Write to Laurence Norman at <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 13:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea<author><![CDATA[Laurence Norman]]></author><category> ukraine</category><category> wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Tragedy of Being a New Mom in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> One in five mothers in the US suffers from mood and anxiety disorders during pregnancy or soon after birth. For many, help is hard to find. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828284/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Jaclyn Ohmer holds her son in Parma, Ohio." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Jaclyn Ohmer holds her son in Parma, Ohio. Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal <span>Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105248"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105248"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anna-mutoh" itemprop="url" rel="author">Anna Mutoh</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 8:02 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mothers-mental-health-women-postpartum-depression-7b548f43"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Jaclyn Ohmer couldn&#39;t wait to have a baby. Before she was pregnant, she bought onesies and beagle-shaped booties. She and her husband, her high-school sweetheart, found out they were having a son and prepared a Star Wars-themed baby room. The 26-year-old from Parma, Ohio, was ready for his arrival.</p><p> Things got harder after he was born in June of last year. Ohmer loved him but she often felt sad. She grew anxious waiting for his next cry. She wasn&#39;t sure she was fit to be a mom.</p><p> When he was shrieking one day, Ohmer had a terrifying thought: “If I put my hand over his mouth, he will be gone. He wouldn&#39;t have to live with me, or go through this.”</p><p> She became increasingly fearful of hurting her baby—and more convinced that her family would be better off without her. Ohmer tried to seek help, but help was hard to find.</p><p> Researchers estimate that one in five new mothers in the US suffers from mood and anxiety disorders during pregnancy and up to a year after giving birth—about 800,000 mothers every year. Yet studies show that a large majority of women who suffer from maternal mental-health disorders aren&#39;t able to get help.</p><p> A major cause is the piecemeal nature of the US healthcare system, where no one medical professional takes responsibility for new mothers and their mental health. Obstetricians, usually the first medical point of contact for new mothers, often don&#39;t specialize in it. Pediatricians focus on the children. Many women seeking help go from doctor to doctor, who struggle to find care amid a shortage of mental-health specialists.</p><p> “Obstetricians may not take ownership. Pediatricians may not take ownership. Psychiatrists may not take ownership,” said Joy Burkhard, founder of Policy Center for Maternal Mental Health, a nonprofit organization. “All of them are putting the mother to each other, and moms fall through the cracks.”</p><p> The US is already <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-maternal-mortality-hits-highest-level-since-1965-f9829776?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the most dangerous</a> place among high-income nations to give birth, with the highest rate of deaths related to pregnancy and childbirth, according to the World Health Organization. The number of women in the US who died during pregnancy or shortly after recently grew to its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-maternal-mortality-hits-highest-level-since-1965-f9829776?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">highest rate since 1965</a> , according to the National Center for Health Statistics, to 33 deaths per 100,000 live births—a number that ranks behind Syria and Uzbekistan.</p><p> Last September, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said mental-health disorders have become the leading cause of maternal death, contributing to nearly one in four pregnancy-related deaths. These include deaths due to suicide and drug overdose during pregnancy or within a year after birth. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828530?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ohmer shuttled between doctors and hospitals in her search for help.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Treatments that have been shown to be effective for maternal mental health, such as psychotherapy, are hard to get. New mothers can also face the stigma of being seen as an unfit parent and have their baby taken away, leaving some reluctant to seek help.</p><p> This week, the Food and Drug Administration is expected to announce a decision on zuranolone, the first pill to treat postpartum depression. If approved, the challenge “will be in making sure people can access it. Because that is the piece that new medication does not solve,” said Dr. Nancy Byatt, a perinatal psychiatrist at UMass Chan Medical School.</p><p> In the struggle to find treatment, Ohmer was no exception.</p><p> Ohmer told her obstetrician at University Hospitals Health System that she often felt sad and anxious. Her OB said those feelings were normal for a new mother, and prescribed her anxiety medication.</p><p> Days later, Ohmer called her husband at work in a panic. She was having suicidal thoughts. Her OB sent her to the emergency room.</p><p> The ER didn&#39;t admit her because Ohmer didn&#39;t have a specific plan to end her life, according to Ohmer and her family. Instead, they told her to go see her primary care doctor at Cleveland Clinic, who set her up with a social worker. The social worker recommended an outpatient postpartum depression care center not affiliated with Cleveland Clinic. It had a one-year wait list.</p><p> Ohmer&#39;s anxiety worsened over the next two months, leading to nightly panic attacks and regular hallucinations. She found herself shuttled between doctors and hospitals. She repeatedly tried to overdose on her anxiety medication. She felt ashamed when an ER nurse suggested she was selfish to have attempted suicide. She was eventually sent for both inpatient and outpatient care at Highland Springs, a general behavioral health facility near Cleveland.</p><p> She went for a month, but said she didn&#39;t feel any better. “Nobody in there could relate to her and talk to her about what she was going through,” said Tiffany McBroom, 51, Ohmer&#39;s mother.</p><p> University Hospitals, Cleveland Clinic and Highland Springs declined to comment, citing patient privacy.</p><p> “The whole time, we&#39;re trusting all these doctors with everyone saying, &#39;Oh, yeah, we&#39;re gonna help you,&#39; but every time it&#39;s been a letdown,” said Nick Ohmer, 25, Ohmer&#39;s husband.</p><h3> Potential causes</h3><p> Scientists aren&#39;t sure what causes postpartum depression and associated mood disorders, but one potential cause could be some women&#39;s sensitivity to fluctuating hormones. A recent study from the <a href="https://news.unchealthcare.org/2023/02/researchers-uncover-mechanisms-of-brexanolone-and-the-role-of-inflammation-in-post-partum-depression/" target="_blank" class="icon none">University of North Carolina School of Medicine</a> suggests inflammation in neural pathways may contribute to the syndrome.</p><p> A growing number of Americans have been diagnosed with mental-health disorders, due in part to factors like increased screening and the toll of the pandemic. But therapists are in short supply. The shortage is even worse for those who focus on new mothers, doctors say. A new field called reproductive psychiatry, which focuses on issues related to women and childbearing, remains relatively unknown even among medical professionals.</p><p> Across the country, there are only <a href="https://www.postpartum.net/get-help/intensive-perinatal-psych-treatment-in-the-us/" target="_blank" class="icon none">three</a> inpatient care facilities dedicated to maternal mental-health care, according to Postpartum Support International, a nonprofit organization, and nearly 30 more that offer outpatient care.</p><p> Brenda Encarnacion, 30, from Santa Clarita, Calif., was voted Most Likely to Know Everyone in high school. She had been working as an extra in movies but became a federal deportation officer because she wanted more financial stability so she could start a family with her husband, Mitchail Encarnacion, 31.</p><p> After their baby girl was born in October 2020, some friends said they saw a change in her mood, but thought it was normal stress. “She was hiding it very well,” her father, Miguel Ayala, 57, said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828581?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Miguel Ayala holds a photo of his daughter, Brenda Encarnacion.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carlos Jaramillo for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Mitchail Encarnacion noticed changes after three months when his wife stopped breast-feeding and she returned to work after maxing out her unpaid 12-week family leave. She would start crying while baking a pie or simply because she wore the “wrong pants,” he said.</p><p> A trained paramedic, he noticed bruise marks on her legs, and one day saw his wife punching her limbs. He begged her to go see a therapist, he said. She began to see a general therapist once a week but stopped when she didn&#39;t find it helpful.</p><p> At each pediatric visit for their daughter, staff routinely asked if she was feeling depressed or had suicidal thoughts, her husband said, but he didn&#39;t feel staff members were really engaging with her. “It was not even like a second, and obviously Brenda&#39;s going to be like, &#39;No.&#39;”</p><p> One day Brenda told her husband that she felt worthless—a sign that suggested she might be having suicidal thoughts, he said. He tried to convince her to leave her job, but they got into an argument because that would mean losing their health insurance.</p><p> The following morning, at around 5 am, Mitchail woke up to a text from Brenda. She apologized and cryptically told him she left so he couldn&#39;t stop her, he said. She told him that she loved him, and to make sure their daughter knew she loved her too. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/fc3e6dc4-5758-4d38-9fa5-2d382d136caf.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In a panic, Mitchail rushed to the local train station that Brenda used for her commute. Her car was there, engine running, and the door unlocked.</p><p> He opened the car door and found his wife inside, dead.</p><p> “She shot herself in the heart,” said Brenda&#39;s father, Ayala.</p><p> Later that day, a package of hundreds of printed photos, downloaded from Brenda&#39;s phone, arrived at the family&#39;s home, Mitchail said—sent by his wife.</p><p> Reasons for suicide are rarely clear or simple. Brenda had kept a lot to herself, said Jeriann Ledner, 32, one of her closest friends. “I have come to terms that she had the disease of postpartum depression, because that is not something that the Brenda we loved would have done,” she said.</p><p> Her husband said he&#39;s now living with his parents, who help him take care of their daughter, and thinks every day about how he could have prevented his wife&#39;s suicide. He said he has since been diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder, anxiety and severe depression.</p><p> Women who attempt suicide typically overdose or cut themselves, both of which can be reversed if caught in time, said Adrienne Griffen, founder of Maternal Mental Health Leadership Alliance, a nonprofit organization focused on health policy. Women who have recently given birth, however, often choose more lethal means of death, including jumping, hanging and shooting. “They are so desperate,” she said.</p><h3> Higher risk</h3><p> The US is the only high-income nation in the world that doesn&#39;t have paid maternity leave, according to the nonprofit Bipartisan Policy Center, and an estimated one in four women return to work within two weeks of giving birth. The stress of juggling a job during the physical and emotional changes of new motherhood puts women at higher risk for postpartum depression, studies have found.</p><p> The statistics are worse for Black women in the US According to the National Center for Health Statistics, their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-maternal-mortality-hits-highest-level-since-1965-f9829776?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">mortality rate</a> was 2.6 times as much as the rate for white women. Public-health experts have attributed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sprinter-tori-bowies-death-reflects-maternal-mortality-crisis-f88d0d8?mod=WTRN_pos2&amp;cx_testId=3&amp;cx_testVariant=cx_160&amp;cx_artPos=1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the disparity</a> in part to less access to healthcare, fewer economic and educational opportunities that contribute to maternal health and unintentional bias among healthcare workers.</p><p> Studies have found that Black mothers are more likely than white mothers to suffer from maternal mental-health disorders, and less likely to get help. Black women who do seek help are often labeled angry and emotional, said Da&#39;na Langford, co-founder of Village of Healing, an Ohio maternal-health care provider run by Black women. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828587?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Denise Williams was &#39;bubbly and could light up the room,&#39; said her sister.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Shane Williams</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Only 5% of psychologists and 6% of psychiatrists are Black, according to industry groups.</p><p> Belinda Staley in New York said the stigma and difficulty of getting help had an impact on her sister, Denise Williams, a former supervisor at Costco and a single mother of two young daughters. Williams was “bubbly and could light up the room,” said her sister, adding, “There was nothing Denise wouldn&#39;t do for her babies.”</p><p> About a year after her first daughter was born in 2018, Williams began to change, Staley said, secluding herself in her room for hours at a time. Then she started asking, “Am I a great mom?” Staley said.</p><p> Williams&#39; apparent depression grew worse when she was pregnant with her second child, Staley said. At times, she would wander outside at 2 am with her toddler, said Charlene Magee, 50, Williams&#39; aunt.</p><p> In 2021, when Williams was about six months pregnant with her second daughter, she went to a police station across the street seeking help and was sent to a hospital psychiatric ward for two weeks, Staley said.</p><p> Putting a woman with a maternal mental-health disorder into a general psychiatric ward is “like offering headache medication to somebody with a stomachache,” said Kallen Thornton, manager of Gender Responsive Services at the Colorado Behavioral Health Administration, a state agency. In addition, she said, “It can damage her identity as a mother and motivation for recovery.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827755?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Belinda Staley; her mother, Linda Magee; and her late sister&#39;s two daughters.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Gabriela Bhaskar for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Williams had her second child a few months later. After she told a drugstore employee she wanted to kill herself and her children, emergency medical services took her to a hospital where she was handcuffed, shackled and labeled a prisoner under arrest in need of medical care, according to medical records. New York&#39;s child protective services took her children, and temporary custody was given to her sister. Williams was discharged three days later.</p><p> Ten days later, Williams&#39; mother called an ambulance because Williams was acting erratically. She died at the hospital two days later, at age 29. The autopsy report said she had died of a pulmonary embolism, a blood clot that travels to the lungs.</p><p> Looking back at how Williams was treated, Staley said, “the help wasn&#39;t there for my sister.”</p><p> Ohmer finally found help at the University of North Carolina Chapel Hill&#39;s Center for Women&#39;s Mood Disorders, one of the three inpatient facilities in the US for maternal mental health.</p><p> While such facilities have existed in other countries for over 60 years, UNC was the first to open specialized inpatient care in the US in 2011, said Dr. Samantha Meltzer-Brody, department chair of the center.</p><p> Two weeks after she got in touch with UNC, Ohmer, her husband and her mother drove the nine hours from Ohio to North Carolina. She was told she would stay anywhere between a week and 20 days. “What if the baby forgets who I am?” she wondered. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828225?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ohmer and her husband play with their son at home.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Within a week, Ohmer passed an evaluation process to get brexanolone, the first drug approved by the FDA in 2019 specifically for postpartum depression. The 60-hour intravenous infusion treatment is made from a derivative of the hormone progesterone.</p><p> Patients need to be monitored during treatment because it can cause <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541054/" target="_blank" class="icon none">excessive sedation and sudden loss of consciousness</a> , but it can start working within days. Speed of recovery is especially important for new mothers to achieve baby bonding, doctors say.</p><p> Without insurance, Ohmer&#39;s total treatment cost for three weeks at UNC, including the infusion and other therapy, would have been over $180,000. With insurance, she paid just under $1,500. The bill still added to the thousands of dollars in medical debt the family had accumulated.</p><p> After two days of the treatment, Ohmer&#39;s family noticed a difference. “Her voice had a lightness,” said her mother.</p><p> Ohmer said she is still working through her mental-health challenges, but they feel much more manageable.</p><p> “Nobody cares about the mental state of moms until you hear about it on the news when they&#39;re already gone or the baby is gone,” she said. “The lack of care, I just don&#39;t understand.”</p><p> <em>Help is available: Call or text the <a href="https://mchb.hrsa.gov/national-maternal-mental-health-hotline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The National Maternal Mental Health Hotline</a> at 1-833-TLC-MAMA (1-833-852-6262). You can also reach the <a href="https://988lifeline.org/" target="_blank" class="icon none">988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline</a> (formerly known as the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline) by dialing or texting 988.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 12:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mothers-mental-health-women-postpartum-depression-7b548f43</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mothers-mental-health-women-postpartum-depression-7b548f43<author><![CDATA[Anna Mutoh]]></author><category>摄影委托</category><category>领导者</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Mood Disorders</category><category> Demographic Health</category><category>健康</category><category>Medical Conditions</category><category> Mental Disorders</category><category> Women&#39;s Health</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>mood disorders</category><category> demographic health</category><category> health</category><category> medical conditions</category><category> mental disorders</category><category> women&#39;s health </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Real Reason You’re Having a Hard Time Getting Things Done at the Office]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Working from home altered our brains. We need more office time to fix them. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828457/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Sam Kelly/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (11) <span>Photo Illustration by Sam Kelly/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (11)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ray-a-smith" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ray A. Smith</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> If you still don&#39;t have your office groove back, there might be a scientific explanation. Hybrid work arrangements mess with our brains.</p><p> Frustrated bosses who survey their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-return-to-office-rate-rises-above-50-for-first-time-since-pandemic-began-11675285071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">half-empty officescapes</a> say it makes no sense that somebody who worked full time in an office before 2020 can&#39;t show up like they used to. But neurologists and behavioral scientists say the collective amnesia for effectively working alongside each other makes perfect sense to them.</p><p> Some workers have lost the muscle memory in their minds required to get jobs done in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-open-office-is-out-seated-privacy-is-in-as-cubicles-make-a-comeback-11663189508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">an open-office setting</a> and, like flabby biceps, that muscle has to be exercised to strengthen, says S. Thomas Carmichael, professor and chair of the neurology department at UCLA&#39;s David Geffen School of Medicine.</p><p> After years of remote work, our brains&#39; selective attention skills and ability to block out distractions is weakened, Carmichael says. Those who prefer to work from home might not like one of his remedies: Make yourself work from the office more often.</p><p> “The brain is really good at understanding contingencies, so if we just say &#39;I&#39;ll just get this done when I&#39;m at home,&#39; we don&#39;t learn it as well,” he says.</p><h3> Drowning in a sea of &#39;what ifs?&#39;</h3><p> Knowing how effective working from home can be has created a simmering unhappiness, says organizational psychologist Cathleen Swody. Many workers lose their uninterrupted autonomy in social office spaces. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828332?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Maryia Babinova says even small office time wasters have become a major annoyance.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Maryia Babinova</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Maryia Babinova, a senior software engineer in New York City, tried going into her office several days a week back in 2021 and found it nearly impossible to be productive.</p><p> “The first 30 to 45 minutes of my day were taken up by saying hello to everybody,” she says.</p><p> Babinova says even small office time wasters have become a major annoyance. A trip to the office coffee machine, for instance, can take as long as 15 minutes when there&#39;s a line. At home, she says, caffeine is at her fingertips, keeping her on task.</p><p> Now, Babinova only shows up in person when her team members visit from another city. At the office, she works on tasks that don&#39;t require a heavy mental lift so she can get them done.</p><p> Constantly comparing 2023&#39;s office realities with alternative remote-work setups can add to workers&#39; readjustment woes, says Laura M. Giurge, an assistant professor at the London School of Economics, who teaches a course on the science of time at work.</p><p> When people start to ponder what life would be like if their circumstances were different, they can rapidly end up drowning in a sea of “what ifs,” a psychological concept known as counterfactual thinking.</p><p> “Now, when we go to the office, we have the counterfactuals of our home offices,” Giurge says. “We know how much better things would be…how much more work we might get done.”</p><p> It&#39;s hard to un-remember how nice it was <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to take the dog for a walk midday</a> , or how helpful it was to log out at 4 pm to get dinner started and log back in later. Running through scenarios of how time could be better spent takes up precious brainpower, distracting us from the real work at hand, psychologists say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> With housing in short supply, developers are converting more empty offices into apartments. But not all buildings are candidates for reuse, even as more than 1 billion square feet of office space sits vacant across the US Photo Illustration: Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>Unsettling quiet</h3><p> Getting used to working with background noise takes time.</p><p> Many workplaces are quieter now because they are less crowded, and that means there can be periods of dead silence punctuated by sudden noise that feels magnified, jarring people again and again all day long. Even toggling between work-from-home solitude one day to a noisy office the next can have a similar effect.</p><p> “We have to habituate ourselves to all those distractions all over again in order to get any good work done,” says Vanessa Bohns, a professor of organizational behavior at Cornell University. She points to research that shows it takes 20 minutes to get used to background noise, but five minutes of silence before bringing back the noise forces the brain&#39;s process to start over again.</p><p> Many workers and a few bosses now view the office as a place to collaborate, but not the only place to do head-down individual work.</p><p> In a large-scale survey published by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">Microsoft</a> last year, 84% of employees cited connecting with co-workers as their key motivation for working in person. More than 70% said they would go to the office more frequently if they knew their direct team members or work friends would be there.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you find it harder to get work done in the office than you did before the pandemic? Why, or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “The data shows we can&#39;t only see the office as a place to get focused work done,” said Colette Stallbaumer, Microsoft&#39;s general manager of Future of Work.</p><p> Lynn Dang, a software developer in the Dallas area, uses her three mandatory office days for face-to-face meetings and work that doesn&#39;t require intense concentration.</p><p> When she transitioned back to the office last year, she noticed she couldn&#39;t concentrate on reading code like she could while working from home. Loud team discussions and overhearing one-sided conversations amid the cubicles from people who were on the phone or dialed into video meetings created a constant assault on her senses.</p><p> “It was like I&#39;m gonna have to find something to do on my to-do list that would make me productive,” she says. “Otherwise I&#39;m going to have to keep working overtime or working over the weekend just to get stuff done.”</p><p> Write to Ray A. Smith at <a href="mailto:Ray.Smith@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ray.Smith@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1<author><![CDATA[Ray A. Smith]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> S. Thomas Carmichael</category><category> Cathleen Swody</category><category> Laura M. Giurge</category><category> Vanessa Bohns</category><category> Colette Stallbaumer</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着地缘政治紧张局势加剧，前往世界第二大经济体的游客减少，东西方鸿沟扩大<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近日，上海机场人烟稀少，旅行社组织的境外旅游来华的人数大幅减少。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：劳尔·阿里亚诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取消Covid-19限制</a>并重新开放边境半年后，几乎没有国际游客前来——这是中国与西方脱钩的另一个迹象，可能会产生长期负面影响。</p><p>外国游客的缺席在北京和上海等主要城市尤其明显，上半年到访这些城市的外国人人数总计不到 2019 年新冠疫情大流行前可比数字的四分之一。</p><p>在全国范围内，第一季度，只有 52,000 人次通过旅行社组织的旅行到达中国大陆，这是有全国数据的最新时期，而 2019 年第一季度有 370 万人次。与往年一样，近一半的游客来自自治岛屿台湾以及中国香港和澳门，而不是美国或欧洲等更远的地方。</p><p> “来自欧洲、美洲、日本和韩国的游客数量都在大幅下降，”半官方的中国旅游协会理事肖千惠在五月份的一次讲话中表示。</p><p>专家表示，海外游客和商人的减少意味着外国人亲眼看到中国并与当地人互动的机会减少，而这是缓解地缘政治紧张局势的一个重要因素。</p><p>游客稀缺也可能导致对华投资减少。研究公司荣鼎集团 (Rhodium Group) 的马克·维茨克 (Mark Witzke) 对政府数据进行的分析显示，第一季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">流入该国的外国直接投资降至</a>200 亿美元，而去年第一季度为 1000 亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019 年，新冠疫情爆发之前，南京的一座陵墓挤满了游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：苏洋/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>外国投资和入境人数下降之际，中国经济停滞不前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">房地产市场低迷</a>，青年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">失业率</a>创历史新高，人们越来越担心中国可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">陷入通货紧缩。</a>与今年前三个月相比，第二季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">中国经济几乎没有增长</a>。</p><p>抵达中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">的航班数量不足</a>是造成抵达人数低的部分原因，航空公司尚未恢复到新冠疫情爆发前提供的服务水平。但中国和海外旅游专家表示，由于中国与西方关系恶化，外国游客也不愿前往，这让他们对访问更加谨慎。</p><p> 6月，美国政府发布旅行建议，警告美国人重新考虑前往中国大陆的旅行，因为所谓的“任意执行当地法律”，包括出境禁令和错误拘留的可能性。</p><p>波士顿商业顾问马特·凯利 (Matt Kelly) 表示，他对 15 年前骑自行车环游中国南方一座风景如画的山城桂林的旅行留下了美好的回忆。他又两次访问中国，但表示今天没有兴趣回去。</p><p> “我会回到我所熟悉的中国吗？是的！”他说。但现在，“中国似乎确实将自己描绘成非常反西方、反美国的人。这让我非常不安。”</p><p>位于宾夕法尼亚州的友好星球旅游公司（Friendly Planet Travel）是一家精品经营商，过去每年向中国派遣多达 1,500 名游客。其创始人兼总裁佩吉·戈德曼 (Peggy Goldman) 表示，自新冠疫情爆发以来，该公司还没有收到过任何要求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">马特·凯利，2008 年在中国桂林。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马特·凯利</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当她的团队研究人们在网上搜索的目的地时，“中国确实处于追踪的底部，”她说。 “围绕中国这个话题存在很多敌意。”</p><p>尽管高盛表示她相信中国最终会再次流行，但该公司尚未将其中国包裹重新上线。</p><p>总部位于奥斯汀的旅游科技公司 Mondee Holdings 的数据显示，2023 年上半年从北美到中国的休闲旅游约为 2019 年同期的 40%。 2019年，Mondee通过旅行社和其他中介机构销售了约50万个从北美飞往中国的航班，约占当年从北美飞往中国的所有航空旅行的五分之一。</p><p>哈里斯·布里肯律师事务所驻西雅图合伙人丹·哈里斯表示，尽管企业高管仍在询问前往中国的旅行，但许多人现在关注的是风险，而过去，他们想知道如何加快签证速度。为在中国的投资提供建议。</p><p> “公司非常非常关心他们的员工去中国。为什么他们不会呢？他提到了中国最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对西方尽职调查公司和其他公司进行调查</a>的消息，其中包括政府对贝恩公司等全球咨询公司进行突击搜查。“除非迫不得已，否则人们不会去中国。”</p><p>哈里斯过去经常去中国北京工作，并在青岛停留购买啤酒和海鲜，他表示，他已告诉一些高管，他们的风险很低。但近年来，在公开批评中国政府后，他本人不再前往。</p><p>中国文化和旅游部没有回应置评请求。</p><p>中国官员最近与美国、欧洲和日本的商业协会举行了会议<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，向他们保证</a>中国仍然欢迎外国投资。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019年以来，张家界国家公园的游客量大幅下降。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：吴永兵/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国驻美国大使谢锋7月份在阿斯彭安全论坛上表示，两国游客应该互相访问。他建议举办旅游论坛并增加航班数量，并呼吁华盛顿调整其旅行建议。</p><p>外国游客的缺席不会像泰国或冰岛那样对中国造成伤害，因为这些国家的经济严重依赖游客。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">目前，中国游客在国内旅游上的支出比 2019 年更多</a>。</p><p>尽管如此，中国仍有许多企业依赖游客。缺乏它们意味着中国失去了向外国人展示更积极形象的机会。</p><p>中国中部的张家界国家公园是电影《阿凡达》中“浮山”的拍摄地，这里有令人惊叹的岩层，截至 5 月中旬，海外游客仅有 25,600 人次，而 2019 年前 5 个月的海外游客人数为 500,000 人次。</p><p>上海导游于雪（Snow Yu）过去带外国人参观的生意很红火，包括在 2017 年为金州勇士队和佐治亚理工学院黄夹克篮球队的高管担任导游。在疫情期间，边境基本关闭，他找了一份英语辅导的临时工作。</p><p>于已经回到了原来的工作岗位，主要带领当地的旅游团。但他们不需要他的英语能力，给的小费也较少。因此，他说他的收入比大流行前减少了近一半。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BD0F48A-0DA4-4CED-8A69-018103B38E36&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> President Biden said on Sunday he sees a potential thaw in relations between the US and China, in a news conference wrapping up the G-7 meeting in Japan. Photo: Susan Walsh/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“世界需要互联，”他说，并补充说来自邻国的英语游客开始回来。</p><p>来自西方和东亚部分地区游客的下降已被俄罗斯游客数量的增加部分抵消，不过中国旅游专家表示，他们的消费有所减少。</p><p>今年6月，张家界国家公园邀请80多家国际旅行社进驻，其中大部分来自俄罗斯。当地官员承诺增加更多从中国北方邻国起飞的航班，或延长从中国其他城市起飞的现有航班。</p><p>旅游官员肖在讲话中呼吁中央政府提供更多支持。他强调，入境旅游可以“以类似于‘乒乓外交’的方式”帮助化解地缘政治紧张局势，他指的是20世纪70年代乒乓球运动员的交流，帮助中美关系解冻。</p><p>他引用了埃隆·马斯克母亲最近访问中国的例子，她在 Instagram 上发布了关于她的经历的积极信息。</p><p>另一个避开中国的群体是外籍人士，他们在前几年充当了中国社会与各自祖国之间的桥梁。许多人邀请家人和朋友来参观。</p><p> 37岁的投资顾问亚历山大·西拉科夫(Alexander Sirakov)去年8月从上海搬回祖国保加利亚。他说，他的外籍朋友圈子里的大多数人也都离开了，包括住在他大院里的 10 个外籍家庭中的 8 个。</p><p> “人们现在认为中国非常遥远，而且有些疏远，”他说。 “四年前正好相反，当时的中国非常开放、充满活力，是一个必去的地方。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——齐丽艳对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给范文欣： <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Medical Conditions</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>health</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>medical conditions</category><category>政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着地缘政治紧张局势加剧，前往世界第二大经济体的游客减少，东西方鸿沟扩大<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近日，上海机场人烟稀少，旅行社组织的境外旅游来华的人数大幅减少。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：劳尔·阿里亚诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取消Covid-19限制</a>并重新开放边境半年后，几乎没有国际游客前来——这是中国与西方脱钩的另一个迹象，可能会产生长期负面影响。</p><p>外国游客的缺席在北京和上海等主要城市尤其明显，上半年到访这些城市的外国人人数总计不到 2019 年新冠疫情大流行前可比数字的四分之一。</p><p>在全国范围内，第一季度，只有 52,000 人次通过旅行社组织的旅行到达中国大陆，这是有全国数据的最新时期，而 2019 年第一季度有 370 万人次。与往年一样，近一半的游客来自自治岛屿台湾以及中国香港和澳门，而不是美国或欧洲等更远的地方。</p><p> “来自欧洲、美洲、日本和韩国的游客数量都在大幅下降，”半官方的中国旅游协会理事肖千惠在五月份的一次讲话中表示。</p><p>专家表示，海外游客和商人的减少意味着外国人亲眼看到中国并与当地人互动的机会减少，而这是缓解地缘政治紧张局势的一个重要因素。</p><p>游客稀缺也可能导致对华投资减少。研究公司荣鼎集团 (Rhodium Group) 的马克·维茨克 (Mark Witzke) 对政府数据进行的分析显示，第一季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">流入该国的外国直接投资降至</a>200 亿美元，而去年第一季度为 1000 亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019 年，新冠疫情爆发之前，南京的一座陵墓挤满了游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：苏洋/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>外国投资和入境人数下降之际，中国经济停滞不前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">房地产市场低迷</a>，青年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">失业率</a>创历史新高，人们越来越担心中国可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">陷入通货紧缩。</a>与今年前三个月相比，第二季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">中国经济几乎没有增长</a>。</p><p>抵达中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">的航班数量不足</a>是造成抵达人数低的部分原因，航空公司尚未恢复到新冠疫情爆发前提供的服务水平。但中国和海外旅游专家表示，由于中国与西方关系恶化，外国游客也不愿前往，这让他们对访问更加谨慎。</p><p> 6月，美国政府发布旅行建议，警告美国人重新考虑前往中国大陆的旅行，因为所谓的“任意执行当地法律”，包括出境禁令和错误拘留的可能性。</p><p>波士顿商业顾问马特·凯利 (Matt Kelly) 表示，他对 15 年前骑自行车环游中国南方一座风景如画的山城桂林的旅行留下了美好的回忆。他又两次访问中国，但表示今天没有兴趣回去。</p><p> “我会回到我所熟悉的中国吗？是的！”他说。但现在，“中国似乎确实将自己描绘成非常反西方、反美国的人。这让我非常不安。”</p><p>位于宾夕法尼亚州的友好星球旅游公司（Friendly Planet Travel）是一家精品经营商，过去每年向中国派遣多达 1,500 名游客。其创始人兼总裁佩吉·戈德曼 (Peggy Goldman) 表示，自新冠疫情爆发以来，该公司还没有收到过任何要求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">马特·凯利，2008 年在中国桂林。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马特·凯利</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当她的团队研究人们在网上搜索的目的地时，“中国确实处于追踪的底部，”她说。 “围绕中国这个话题存在很多敌意。”</p><p>尽管高盛表示她相信中国最终会再次流行，但该公司尚未将其中国包裹重新上线。</p><p>总部位于奥斯汀的旅游科技公司 Mondee Holdings 的数据显示，2023 年上半年从北美到中国的休闲旅游约为 2019 年同期的 40%。 2019年，Mondee通过旅行社和其他中介机构销售了约50万个从北美飞往中国的航班，约占当年从北美飞往中国的所有航空旅行的五分之一。</p><p>哈里斯·布里肯律师事务所驻西雅图合伙人丹·哈里斯表示，尽管企业高管仍在询问前往中国的旅行，但许多人现在关注的是风险，而过去，他们想知道如何加快签证速度。为在中国的投资提供建议。</p><p> “公司非常非常关心他们的员工去中国。为什么他们不会呢？他提到了中国最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对西方尽职调查公司和其他公司进行调查</a>的消息，其中包括政府对贝恩公司等全球咨询公司进行突击搜查。“除非迫不得已，否则人们不会去中国。”</p><p>哈里斯过去经常去中国北京工作，并在青岛停留购买啤酒和海鲜，他表示，他已告诉一些高管，他们的风险很低。但近年来，在公开批评中国政府后，他本人不再前往。</p><p>中国文化和旅游部没有回应置评请求。</p><p>中国官员最近与美国、欧洲和日本的商业协会举行了会议<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，向他们保证</a>中国仍然欢迎外国投资。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019年以来，张家界国家公园的游客量大幅下降。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：吴永兵/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国驻美国大使谢锋7月份在阿斯彭安全论坛上表示，两国游客应该互相访问。他建议举办旅游论坛并增加航班数量，并呼吁华盛顿调整其旅行建议。</p><p>外国游客的缺席不会像泰国或冰岛那样对中国造成伤害，因为这些国家的经济严重依赖游客。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">目前，中国游客在国内旅游上的支出比 2019 年更多</a>。</p><p>尽管如此，中国仍有许多企业依赖游客。缺乏它们意味着中国失去了向外国人展示更积极形象的机会。</p><p>中国中部的张家界国家公园是电影《阿凡达》中“浮山”的拍摄地，这里有令人惊叹的岩层，截至 5 月中旬，海外游客仅有 25,600 人次，而 2019 年前 5 个月的海外游客人数为 500,000 人次。</p><p>上海导游于雪（Snow Yu）过去带外国人参观的生意很红火，包括在 2017 年为金州勇士队和佐治亚理工学院黄夹克篮球队的高管担任导游。在疫情期间，边境基本关闭，他找了一份英语辅导的临时工作。</p><p>于已经回到了原来的工作岗位，主要带领当地的旅游团。但他们不需要他的英语能力，给的小费也较少。因此，他说他的收入比大流行前减少了近一半。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BD0F48A-0DA4-4CED-8A69-018103B38E36&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> President Biden said on Sunday he sees a potential thaw in relations between the US and China, in a news conference wrapping up the G-7 meeting in Japan. Photo: Susan Walsh/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“世界需要互联，”他说，并补充说来自邻国的英语游客开始回来。</p><p>来自西方和东亚部分地区游客的下降已被俄罗斯游客数量的增加部分抵消，不过中国旅游专家表示，他们的消费有所减少。</p><p>今年6月，张家界国家公园邀请80多家国际旅行社进驻，其中大部分来自俄罗斯。当地官员承诺增加更多从中国北方邻国起飞的航班，或延长从中国其他城市起飞的现有航班。</p><p>旅游官员肖在讲话中呼吁中央政府提供更多支持。他强调，入境旅游可以“以类似于‘乒乓外交’的方式”帮助化解地缘政治紧张局势，他指的是20世纪70年代乒乓球运动员的交流，帮助中美关系解冻。</p><p>他引用了埃隆·马斯克母亲最近访问中国的例子，她在 Instagram 上发布了关于她的经历的积极信息。</p><p>另一个避开中国的群体是外籍人士，他们在前几年充当了中国社会与各自祖国之间的桥梁。许多人邀请家人和朋友来参观。</p><p> 37岁的投资顾问亚历山大·西拉科夫(Alexander Sirakov)去年8月从上海搬回祖国保加利亚。他说，他的外籍朋友圈子里的大多数人也都离开了，包括住在他大院里的 10 个外籍家庭中的 8 个。</p><p> “人们现在认为中国非常遥远，而且有些疏远，”他说。 “四年前正好相反，当时的中国非常开放、充满活力，是一个必去的地方。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——齐丽艳对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给范文欣： <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Medical Conditions</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>health</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>medical conditions</category><category>政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category></item></channel></rss>